1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,840
Somewhere out there.

2
00:00:01,840 --> 00:00:05,320
The odds say there is probably alien life.

3
00:00:05,320 --> 00:00:06,560
Maybe a little.

4
00:00:06,560 --> 00:00:08,200
Maybe oceans of it.

5
00:00:08,200 --> 00:00:12,160
Which raises a question almost nobody actually stops to ask.

6
00:00:12,160 --> 00:00:16,200
Even if they are real, could they ever actually get here?

7
00:00:16,200 --> 00:00:17,680
Could anything?

8
00:00:17,680 --> 00:00:21,560
Stan looks up at the stars half expecting an easy yes.

9
00:00:21,560 --> 00:00:24,200
But the true answer hides one of the most staggering facts

10
00:00:24,200 --> 00:00:26,440
about the universe you will ever sit with.

11
00:00:26,440 --> 00:00:29,560
And once you see it, you will never look at that night sky

12
00:00:29,560 --> 00:00:31,320
the same way again.

13
00:00:31,320 --> 00:00:33,800
Start with the closest possible neighbor.

14
00:00:33,800 --> 00:00:36,680
The nearest star to us other than our own sun

15
00:00:36,680 --> 00:00:39,000
is called Proxima Centauri.

16
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:41,400
It is about four light years away.

17
00:00:41,400 --> 00:00:42,720
Four.

18
00:00:42,720 --> 00:00:45,960
That sounds almost walkable, cosmically speaking.

19
00:00:45,960 --> 00:00:49,760
But a light year is the distance light travels in a year.

20
00:00:49,760 --> 00:00:54,200
And light is the fastest thing that exists around 186,000

21
00:00:54,200 --> 00:00:56,360
miles every single second.

22
00:00:56,360 --> 00:00:59,120
The light landing in your eye from that star tonight

23
00:00:59,120 --> 00:01:01,560
left it more than four years ago.

24
00:01:01,560 --> 00:01:05,360
So four is hiding something enormous.

25
00:01:05,360 --> 00:01:08,840
Because here's the catch that changes everything.

26
00:01:08,840 --> 00:01:11,000
We cannot travel at the speed of light.

27
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:12,960
Nothing with mass can.

28
00:01:12,960 --> 00:01:15,200
Pushing any object up to light speed

29
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:17,400
would take an infinite amount of energy.

30
00:01:17,400 --> 00:01:19,480
The universe simply forbids it.

31
00:01:19,480 --> 00:01:24,040
So the real question becomes how fast can we actually go?

32
00:01:24,040 --> 00:01:25,720
And the answer is humbling.

33
00:01:25,720 --> 00:01:27,760
Our fastest spacecraft.

34
00:01:27,800 --> 00:01:30,160
If you aimed it straight at that nearest star

35
00:01:30,160 --> 00:01:32,200
would not take hundreds of years.

36
00:01:32,200 --> 00:01:34,360
It would take tens of thousands.

37
00:01:34,360 --> 00:01:36,760
Voyager, our most famous probe,

38
00:01:36,760 --> 00:01:40,120
would need roughly 77,000 years to get there.

39
00:01:40,120 --> 00:01:42,160
Let that land with one number.

40
00:01:42,160 --> 00:01:44,160
Voyager has been flying away from Earth

41
00:01:44,160 --> 00:01:45,960
for almost 50 years now.

42
00:01:45,960 --> 00:01:48,440
Faster than any of us will ever move.

43
00:01:48,440 --> 00:01:51,520
And in all that time, it has traveled about one light day

44
00:01:51,520 --> 00:01:55,160
from home, one day at the speed of light.

45
00:01:55,160 --> 00:01:58,880
The nearest star is over 1,500 light days away.

46
00:01:58,880 --> 00:02:00,720
We have been going for half a century

47
00:02:00,720 --> 00:02:02,840
and we are barely off the porch.

48
00:02:02,840 --> 00:02:06,720
So now flip it around and put yourself in the aliens' shoes.

49
00:02:06,720 --> 00:02:10,040
For them to cross that same impossible gulf and reach us,

50
00:02:10,040 --> 00:02:12,200
they would need technology that to us

51
00:02:12,200 --> 00:02:13,920
would look like pure magic.

52
00:02:13,920 --> 00:02:16,200
They would either have to travel at a massive fraction

53
00:02:16,200 --> 00:02:18,960
of light speed, which takes amounts of energy

54
00:02:18,960 --> 00:02:20,960
that are almost beyond imagining,

55
00:02:20,960 --> 00:02:24,200
or they would have to break the rules of space itself.

56
00:02:24,240 --> 00:02:27,640
Physicists actually have one idea for that, the warp drive.

57
00:02:27,640 --> 00:02:29,920
The trick is you do not move through space,

58
00:02:29,920 --> 00:02:31,800
you move space around your ship,

59
00:02:31,800 --> 00:02:34,320
like a surfer riding a wave.

60
00:02:34,320 --> 00:02:37,000
And the math genuinely works.

61
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:39,600
The only problem is it requires a kind of matter

62
00:02:39,600 --> 00:02:42,400
with negative energy that, as far as we know,

63
00:02:42,400 --> 00:02:45,200
has never been found and may not exist at all.

64
00:02:45,200 --> 00:02:48,560
Even our single best real attempt, tiny probes,

65
00:02:48,560 --> 00:02:51,240
pushed by lasers to a fifth of light speed,

66
00:02:51,240 --> 00:02:54,360
would still take 20 years to reach the nearest star.

67
00:02:54,360 --> 00:02:57,120
And that project quietly stalled.

68
00:02:57,120 --> 00:02:59,760
This is not a new puzzle, by the way.

69
00:02:59,760 --> 00:03:03,920
Back in 1950, a brilliant physicist named Enrico Fermi

70
00:03:03,920 --> 00:03:07,320
was just chatting over lunch about the chances of alien life

71
00:03:07,320 --> 00:03:08,760
and he asked a simple question

72
00:03:08,760 --> 00:03:11,360
that has haunted science ever since.

73
00:03:11,360 --> 00:03:12,600
Where is everybody?

74
00:03:13,800 --> 00:03:17,280
Think about it, the galaxy is unbelievably huge

75
00:03:17,280 --> 00:03:20,520
and unbelievably old billions of years.

76
00:03:20,520 --> 00:03:23,840
If intelligent life is common and crossing space

77
00:03:23,840 --> 00:03:26,960
were doable, then somebody somewhere

78
00:03:26,960 --> 00:03:29,760
in all that time should have shown up.

79
00:03:29,760 --> 00:03:33,920
And yet, silence, they call it the Fermi paradox

80
00:03:33,920 --> 00:03:35,520
and one of the simplest answers to it

81
00:03:35,520 --> 00:03:37,280
is also the most humbling.

82
00:03:37,280 --> 00:03:40,040
Maybe nobody shows up because nobody can.

83
00:03:40,040 --> 00:03:43,400
Here is the quiet, strange truth this points to.

84
00:03:43,400 --> 00:03:46,280
The universe might be absolutely teeming with life

85
00:03:46,280 --> 00:03:49,080
and it could still be true that none of them ever meet,

86
00:03:49,120 --> 00:03:50,960
not because they are not there,

87
00:03:50,960 --> 00:03:53,240
but because every civilization is stranded

88
00:03:53,240 --> 00:03:56,000
on its own little island of a solar system.

89
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:59,240
Separated by gulfs so vast that even light,

90
00:03:59,240 --> 00:04:02,080
the fastest thing in existence takes years

91
00:04:02,080 --> 00:04:05,560
and centuries and thousands of years to cross.

92
00:04:05,560 --> 00:04:08,680
We might be surrounded by neighbors we can never visit.

93
00:04:08,680 --> 00:04:12,000
And it cuts both ways, which is the part we forget.

94
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:13,800
We are not reaching them either.

95
00:04:13,800 --> 00:04:17,000
For all our rockets and telescopes and ambition,

96
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:20,240
we have exactly one probe a single light day out

97
00:04:20,240 --> 00:04:22,440
after 50 years of trying.

98
00:04:22,440 --> 00:04:25,120
The aliens may very well be real.

99
00:04:25,120 --> 00:04:29,040
They just cannot get to us and we cannot get to them.

100
00:04:29,040 --> 00:04:30,880
The silence in the sky might not mean

101
00:04:30,880 --> 00:04:32,840
the universe is empty at all.

102
00:04:32,840 --> 00:04:35,120
It might just mean it is so full

103
00:04:35,120 --> 00:04:39,640
and so impossibly spread out that everyone is alone together.

104
00:04:39,640 --> 00:04:41,480
So the next time you look up and wonder

105
00:04:41,480 --> 00:04:45,040
if anyone is out there, the honest answer is probably.

106
00:04:45,040 --> 00:04:48,040
Somewhere they simply cannot reach you

107
00:04:48,040 --> 00:04:51,200
and you cannot reach them not because the universe is empty

108
00:04:51,200 --> 00:04:53,760
but because it is so unimaginably vast

109
00:04:53,760 --> 00:04:56,160
that even light strains to cross it.

110
00:04:56,160 --> 00:04:59,240
We are not alone, we are just very, very far apart.

111
00:05:00,440 --> 00:05:03,280
And a universe that big, that full

112
00:05:03,280 --> 00:05:06,720
and that far flung is not a sad thought.

113
00:05:06,720 --> 00:05:08,400
It might be the most astonishing thing

114
00:05:08,400 --> 00:05:09,720
about being here at all.
